The Prague stock market is plunging into a slump.
After the sharp drop in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
The transactions in ČEZ shares amounted to almost half of the normal daily turnover.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed Monday's slump with another six percentage points at the start of Tuesday's trading.
This time, the reason for the bust was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market reaction to the vote of the US House of Representatives, which had refused to support a financial sector stabilisation plan, is reflected.
The fall of stocks in Asia
Shares in Asian stock markets fell dramatically on Tuesday, although indices were able to offset some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng stock market in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points during the day, but later recovered some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while markets were closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney stock market lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan stock market fell by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide", said Hong Kong's chief monetary officer Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy itself, so independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are on a par with those in the United States.
The American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the draft for supporting the financial system, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected by the break-in.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a financial-system bailout plan that would cost up to $700 billion.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
In Bush's view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks were in a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indexes posted their biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, a similar drop from 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as there were signs that the draft would not pass the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes a concession: the U.S. government is allowed to pump $700 billion into the banks.
The top representatives of the American Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement on financial assistance for the American financial system.
The vote on this is due early next week.
The American legislators have made a breakthrough in talks to pass a rescue plan in the form of a $700 billion bailout of the American financial system.
However, this does not mean victory.
The members of Congress have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the bill and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
The Senate is expected to vote on the plan by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notification that the plan is being adopted should be the first major psychological factor for a revival in financial markets.
However, there is a 're-awakening' afterwards, because of the complex mechanisms for how markets could be helped in practice.
The plan must be effective.
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differences on what a package to stabilize the market should look like", said Democratic House Speaker Nancy Pelosi.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
Representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to finalize the government fund.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the aid is limited to the minimum necessary.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The recovery plan must be continued, but I think we are on track", says Paulson.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also having a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim is to reassure investors against trading in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone where a congressional decision could affect trading on Monday.
But it is still unclear when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, and there is uncertainty about whether negotiations could still fail at the last minute over a problem.
The legislators hope to pass it in the next few days.
The law will still undergo some changes.
The total amount of aid allocated to the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
The initial 350 billion dollars are to be made available as quickly as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the remaining money if it feels the program is not doing its job, and that's another $100 billion and then the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
The President has veto power over this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program has remained the same, which was based on obtaining financing to buy back bad mortgage securities that have fallen in value because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to pay back their mortgages.
"We've worked it all out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "appreciated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Restriction of golden parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, ending benefits and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies involved in the programme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The Treasury should run this.
"We have worked very hard and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners who have problems paying off their mortgages.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys, with the goal of reducing the monthly costs for borrowers and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, but will be very difficult to implement.
"This is because you don't know what the mechanism is and what the price is for buying up the problem assets.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses", Marek told the server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not decisive in Marek's view.
"It is far more important that Congress agrees to support the plan and pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement to adopt is the most important thing at this moment", Marek stressed.
Duel on the edge of a knife, MP3 player versus cell phone.
We will advise you on your choice
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls yet.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons to get yourself a player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It's hard to buy a really expensive turntable for your home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album on.
Once such musical innovations are released, they do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
But if you have any LPs of Art Rock, Jazz or Blues on your shelf, you probably dream of at least one of these.
So it's the same with music on the go, so with compressed music, in simple terms -- music in MP3 format.
Here again, there are price and quality categories.
It may not be acceptable for one person to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably find it hard to get headphones for twenty crowns off the market.
Two extremes, with enough room in between for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can do much more than just play music, but they don't even hint at what cell phones can do.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, it has a better camera, a worse camera, and maybe even navigate.
And if you add in the smartphones and the communicators, you've got almost a little computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can take pictures.
But the universality of cell phones also has its drawbacks.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you'll need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy-consuming activities.
Few phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more powerful.
So you should expect the cheap phones to play only a few hours of music.
If you still use the phone occasionally, buy a charger for the office - even for more expensive devices - to be safe.
MP3 players, you won't have this problem, even the less good ones can last at least nine hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem is when you want to play the music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small number of these devices have a USB port, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can play music directly to a storage device, but few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in cell phones without reduction.
With players, you don't need special software except for exceptions (iPod).
All you have to do is feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most cell phones and players create a music library of their own, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user rating.
Some devices only display the tree structure of the address book, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, cell phones can be more
When choosing a particular device, you should ask about the battery life, storage capacity, quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If you prefer music as a backdrop and listen to it briefly every day, for example on the tram, then any phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which is something almost every cell phone can do.
You also don't have to control what music formats a phone or a player can handle.
MP3 is created by everyone, and most of the music you get is going to be in that format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better cell phones also make it possible to buy music online.
All you have to do is access the relevant pages of a provider (or another provider) via the mobile Internet and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can be a powerful argument for getting a music phone.
Unfortunately, the providers' offerings are poor and usually limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest.
But it is generally assumed that this kind of music sales (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone.
If you feel like listening to something, reach for the phone in your jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it does matter whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you can get a decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most people will be that they don't have regular headphones.
The best and most technically advanced phones with a 3.5 mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players lies in the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - players can really be used by anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a misplaced mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous data bill.
Which device should you use?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (M2 type, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will suffice.
But be careful.
The basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, you can go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or whatever.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you will not have to put more than EUR 1 500 on the table.
If you are a more demanding listener, you may prefer to use specialized cell phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate MP3 controls, and the ease of use is thus close to that of a single MP3 player.
The most advanced is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold individually.
The same services in the same price range of up to four thousand kroner, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours maximum) are provided by MP3 players of the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider will be coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I did .
The Czech mobile market is quite mature, with Czech operators offering virtually all the services offered by their Western European partners.
However, something is missing here - a virtual supplier that forces the classic ones to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't keep you waiting much longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really makes a fight legend.
It may seem paradoxical, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration rate of well over 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
This is often echoed by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a traditional provider with its own network would not have much of an opportunity (and would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which was then also met by traditional mobile operators.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the Czech Republic is able to comply with the new rules.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look long for examples.
In February this year we reported on the launch of the virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the company managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not require relatively high costs to build, operate and maintain a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually present themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, but often with a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaply as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to target a non-cliché audience.
This is because this provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real people choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust", says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of the virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also take hold in the Czech Republic.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not provided any evidence that the measures in question are imputable to the State.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering.'
The Czech Republic is out of luck, mobile operators say
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"While we are talking about expanding this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not looking very promising.
It will be more likely to be Mobilking's market entry in other countries in our region", says Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
GTS Novera has long shown interest in launching a virtual mobile operator and wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate sector.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them", said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times will come.
Non-official information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area", said Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2's press department in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in rare agreement with O2's statement, adds: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on".
She adds: "T-Mobile's network will hardly have a virtual provider by the end of the year.
We would have to have a concrete offer at this point to think so short term".
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet established the existence of a market failure in the market for the provision of services.
Miroslav Čepický comments: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the best from the customer's point of view.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.'
The responsible authorities - working hand in hand with the providers
The behaviour of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be given easy access to the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to anything is also evidence of the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
The pressure on ČTÚ was probably the strongest at the time when U:fon entered the market, from T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is a good argument for not allowing a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and in particular on its services.'
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other advanced countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
The Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS) is the sole owner of the Office.
The Commission has not yet decided on the proposal for a directive.
'The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would be possible only after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not of sufficient interest to the traditional suppliers", says Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our inquiry.
The Commission has not yet received any information on the situation in the Union.
This is more than a concern for an authority which represents the interests of consumers and is supposed to ensure, among other things, that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: 'In foreign countries where virtual operators operate normally, their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in mobile phone prices.'
However, the pressure to ensure the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not in the interest of ÚOHS.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
'The Authority has not detected any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant position on the market and therefore does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its activities on the market.
The telecommunications regulator is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual operators", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious issues.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by ČTÚ, which considers telecommunications to be a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, take a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the mobile operator has - logically - a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily has a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if this argument is not accepted, the fact that three mobile operators are strikingly similar should at least serve as a warning to ÚOHS.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the ČTÚ's powers to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised that it would improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if no one's looking
The first is the existence of pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the information provided by the Member States is not used to mislead consumers.
Own mobile phone services are provided by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to selected customers.
The fun of it is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As a key customer, he will then receive special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
'If there are cases you describe, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract, which we will then deal with, which could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company concerned,' Martina Kemrová answered our question on this problem.
However, it is unlikely that this will not be discussed by the operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may have thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such a practice.
The fact is that these companies do not generate negligible profits from their activities and, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out that there are potential problems: "The law allows for this type of speculation, but the services of these companies are used by only a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name and therefore cannot be fully used by them as normal customers of mobile operators.'
But that alone would have to make the CTU seem at least strange.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionizing radiation.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a fairly strong competence to detect such activities and, if it does not wish to, does not have to be satisfied with the declaration by the providers that they were not aware of them and that their terms and conditions prohibited it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As already emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers has led to a significant drop in prices for the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulatory bodies intervened, which were not trying to protect the interests of the mobile operators but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the first virtual operator and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
In our experience we cannot escape the impression that uncertainty in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But we're not throwing the gun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be back on track.
If an operator allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to call than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech national anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my homeland at a ceremony on the occasion of the day of Czech statehood.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo vocals, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocals were performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions at once.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national anthem is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had selected singers with young, representative voices who are distinctive and popular for the solo versions.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction for both and then for the choir, so that the text would be well understood, so that a harmony would be created", says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed on the stage of the Ständtheater in 1834 in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people took it on spontaneously.
The first stanza of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
