The Prague transport companies will also be promoting for the first time on a chip on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague's transport companies as the date when the first passengers on a subway, tram or bus will board with an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the Commission's proposals are implemented.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it simultaneously played on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons are also available online from yesterday on the transport companies' website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon.
Those who use the Internet can really forget the window at subway stations where they have to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon online, and it is played on the Opencard at one of the city library's 13 branches.
"At these points, travellers also have a desk with trained staff to advise on online shopping and to display the coupon on the map", says Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the opencard at self-service machines, which are located in some subway lobbies.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket counters, and passengers may have noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there will be 80", Opatrný adds.
The coupon is controlled by an automated machine instead of the driver
The machines that will be working from tomorrow are easy to operate.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the pre-purchased coupon will play itself out.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
The main means of transport are the suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which mainly serve the inhabitants of the Central Bohemian municipalities.
"On trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, train attendants have readers to check the validity of the time and zone coupons", explains Filip Drápal of Ropid, the ticket control organisation that compiles timetables for Prague's transport operators.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver but the open card must be placed in a marked place on the side of the ticket office.
This allows the driver to check the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, it is easier to ask the driver for this information", Drápal says.
Passengers who do not use suburban buses and do not know when the coupon expires can go to the vending machines where the coupons are played on the card.
This will display the information on the validity of his documents on the display of the apparatus.
The Sudetenlanders demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had requested in 1945 that the Bohemian Forest be annexed to the United States.
This is shown by a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
In 1945 some Sudeten Germans reportedly appealed to the U.S. president with this hope.
This is shown, among other things, by a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau ask the American president in the letter not to allow the return of the "Sudden Gull" - which had been taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and want to be sure of the words that the American troops are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", says a letter signed with the words "People who care about the fate of the Sudetenland".
Since the annexation of Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protective rule over the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that you, without regard for the views of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this territory, attribute to a foreign state which has oppressed and tried to eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing to the Allied victory", the letter reads.
