Rats have feelings too
A rat or a cockroach fleeing danger, does that mean it feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings too.
But how can you check if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions by renowned scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove this so far, whereas we can't even prove that other humans have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But once we turn to another species and we address issues of perception or consciousness in general, we enter a dead end because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what many other animals do: it pretends to be dead, flies away, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, leading some scientists to conclude that there is a similar subjective experience.
I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
For one thing, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there's reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature is likely to be the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is related to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not dependent on language, it would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, however it may be made, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or analyzed by our own experience because of the special hardware, then its research presents us with great problems.
Most of my talk is about the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that is supposed to be more scientifically accessible.
You could study the processes of consciousness in animals without regard to their content, and that's exactly what happens in studies of primate short-term memory, especially the example of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick took, is shifting to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What about the sensations?
I'm going to take it back to the fact that an emotional system like fear is activated in a brain that's aware of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of the immune system located in the brain (or its effects, such as physical reactions) is recorded in working memory.
So, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
In connection with the nature of language, subtle gradations of perception result because we can use words and grammar to differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brainstem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, but focusing more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in intersex sensations.
I cannot contradict this in theory, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what seems to be fear in rats and humans probably feels that way in both cases: But how can you test whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
Does a cockroach run away from danger if it feels fear?
In my view, mere similarity of behavior is not proof of similarity of experience.
While neural comparison is helpful: Rats and humans have similar brainstems, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove that in humans, how would you prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'm more interested in exploring emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
But at any rate, we're seeing some progress at the neural level, if you measure the same thing in rats and humans.
Just as I don't study language and consciousness in rats, nor sensation, I don't know if they exist.
You may think I'm short-sighted, but I'd rather be moving forward than running into a wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist, you know.
