The debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of applicants for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California Studies and senior director of the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of Not As Good As You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choice.
The Spanish voters are a complicated task.
Barack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
The Obama campaign mentioned that "African-American and Hispanic students are less likely to graduate than white students" - which is true.
To close this achievement gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition period in education for those who are just learning English.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in languages other than English, clashes with his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles.
The majority of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived in the country, are learning English.
Yet in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-graders passed the state math test at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the fourth-year students scored well on their English test.
This amazing success was achieved by other methods than those preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street School emphasizes review and practice, constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
The school also practices the approach of teaching in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be concerned about, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasises the almost exclusive use of English in vocational education.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico, and 12 months later you would walk into the classroom and not recognize him.
"It works", she remarked, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with large numbers of Hispanic and other English-speaking students?
The school's performance would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within his own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by remarking that people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to close the achievement gap, he should carefully consider education models that work, rather than belittling and trivializing them.
