Brewster breaks his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him the greatest long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to complete the 42.2-kilometer distance in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
By winning the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous record of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has set his 26th world record in his varied career, having won at least one world title or set a world record on every mile of the track from one kilometer to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie missed the Beijing Olympics marathon, perhaps overstating his fear that air pollution might worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In near-ideal conditions - sunny and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya switched to long distance, the record time for marathon has fallen by more than 2 minutes in the last 10 years since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won in Berlin in 1998 with a result of 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and could not train for a week.
Apparently, he came back from his break refreshed and not rusty.
"I'm so happy", he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I started training a week ago and I had some concerns today, but in the end it was great".
He has been criticized -- particularly in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival -- for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records in the race.
But this criticism hardly harms the size of the breaststroke as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyan riders on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the midpoint of the track in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pace makers had slowed down.
With just over three miles to go, Gebrselassie made his final start to separate himself from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's category, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, finished a remarkable year by setting the seventh fastest time ever in 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games due to problems described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She planned her run cleverly, first letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners out but overtaking them after 20 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardship of black life in a city of a very special kind.
Hidden among the lush greenery of Orlando's surrounding theme parks, a few miles from the glittering, loud, gigantic bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture are evident.
Eatonville, the first all-black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the town with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, two schools and no jail".
Today, it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to honor the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city she describes, and the one that made her a tourist destination by including her in the Florida Travel Guide produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression, is and remains in many ways a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, solid and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing".
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told", says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a member of the city's oldest church.
It has to be true".
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 people with a poverty rate twice the national average.
It is a bastion of literature on the one hand, and an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised, black culture of the rural South that has its roots in American slavery.
It's no surprise that the inhabitants here are both proud and wary.
And rightly so, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from her heart and were written in the style of oral history, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide changed the town, which is located very close to Route 77, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida, into the setting of black history and human drama.
Naughty like Oscar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Over the road to the left", she wrote, "is the brown-and-white-painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always tends, although he can hardly read or write".
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever-ever fits in classrooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
This was certainly not a guidebook.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual innuendo.
She added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into town drunk, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable dress style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised her.
"People were always glad to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long", he added as he rocked his chair on a back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were in ruins.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no big memorial service, no big public readings.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage in the least", says Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turning point came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to build a five-lane freeway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western suburbs.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the community's relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At that time, a lot of white boys would come and throw oranges and stuff at the people sitting on the sidelines", said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car".
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration, calling its decision in Brown v. School Board "insulting rather than respectful of my race".
Residents now say that while the desegregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-esteem of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening", says N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group protecting the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained until teachers and students no longer came from the same place, she added.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide", Ms. Nathiri said.
But civil rights helped make room for other Zora Neale Hurstons -- black writers, actors, and artists who pushed aside prejudice, as she did, with positive self-esteem and statements like, "How can anyone deny themselves the joy of my company?
I don't understand what you're saying".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-lauded Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on bookshelves, making it a part of the American literary canon once again.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community started planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county could destroy by building the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many return for the celebration every January.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway brought life to the city, accelerated the process at top speed, and created real pride", said Ms Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project has contributed to a change in the city's image.
More and more train travelers arrived, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending the church since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past.
Eatonville was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a distinctive Florida town, just six miles from downtown Orlando, and it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rains, as small as when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders seeking to understand Eatonville's history and significance are still often treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission and certain things - like the mural of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men working in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a taste for dark red, still fear that their barricaded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew in size, a heightened sense of homeland pride was born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, no worse or better, and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It's the genuine love for this city that you can hear in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city government or the police department, who he says could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon the other Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city".
Here in New York, we speak financial Latin fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they would not even realize they were in the middle of a debacle.
You would never believe that above their heads, in their shoebox-like glass-fronted offices, bankers and hedge fund managers who have a monopoly on New York City are having the worst day of horror every day since the 1929 stock market crash.
Suppliers still push metal teacups along sidewalks with loud bangs and carry tablets loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos still roam between apartments like human pack animals, carrying around 50 ironing shirts that hang from a yoke-like pole on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bagels at sidewalk food stands and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, with all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Even though I had decided to put my duty out on time for the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people lined up.
Not at the cash machines to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, I later learned from Starr, my "personal bank clerk with a license", were queuing for the same reason I was.
But unlike me, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places they were commuting from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrift banks (a bit like a building society), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state and say they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks quietly went bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into receivership, and as New Yorkers drove home for the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank with $440 billion in savings, was looking for a buyer to save it.
Fearing another collapse, the office and store workers in line in front of me took their cash to a bank that was considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most of the bailout purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have been acquiring fluent financial literacy in recent weeks.
A woman on the phone at my Chinese family supermarket referred to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its skinny-looking CEO Dick Fuld with as much familiarity as if she were cursing at a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-something uniformed concierge at my apartment building, has moved on from our usual conversation about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
"I have all my savings in money market funds now", she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not taking any more risks".
Muslim graves desecrated during right-wing slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a leftist from the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party of Austria, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, to represent the organization Cities Against Islamization.
They wear signs in the style of traffic signs with a mosque, crossed with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a grave at a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend that far-right parties recorded significant gains in the country's parliamentary election.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves at the cemetery in Traun near Linz were badly damaged in an organized action, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Star on some of the graves, but criminal officials say this is an attempt to cover up the motive of the extremists, who are driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear if the incident is in any way connected to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the grave desecration, which took place as the Muslim religious month of Ramadan draws to a close.
At the same time, Austria is going through a period of conscientiousness after the country's rightward shift in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the FPÖ, who won 18% of the vote, advocated a ban on headscarves and burqas and even expressed his dislike of foods commonly associated with Islam.
In his last speech in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that these are political symbols of a continuing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the election, which indicate that the extreme right is the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
