Paul Gadd was not personally present".
As required by the sex offender registry, Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he was planning to travel abroad.
He must notify the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police seven days before his planned departure.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of up to five years.
Kent police said they wouldn't discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokeswoman for Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country and abroad".
"We believe it is easier to control someone in the UK because we have a comprehensive system to effectively prevent any potential risks".
"Kent Police's top priority is to protect the people of Kent and we are working closely to monitor the behaviour of registered sex offenders in the country to minimise any risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, Glitter flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities wouldn't let him through passport control and he flew back and forth to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also refused him entry and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and border officials insisted he return to Britain.
Finally, he arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and remained there while his lawyer David Corker went to Uxbridge District Court in west London, as Scotland Yard had successfully applied for permission to require him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been jailed for four months in the UK in 1999 for possessing child abuse images.
The Home Office said that Home Secretary Jacqui Smith was reassured and pleased that Glitter had been prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
