Drivers who may relapse due to alcohol levels will have to install the 'alcohol lock'.
The authority orders that the driver who has three official alcohol-related penalties install this system in his car that prohibits him from starting the car while drunk.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Prosecutor General's Office, which said it was a pilot project that would last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialize the driver, so that he receives a course for re-education in traffic behaviour.
In addition to the Attorney General's Office, experience has shown that the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automotive Safety will also participate.
Statistics show that between 30 and 75% of drivers who were reported for DUI more than once returned to driving.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver has taken an alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is found to be higher than the permissible level.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, and the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study conducted in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of infractions in the first year after their introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes an offence.
And to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented through the usual channels, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is not yet available in any shop on the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
