Some children talk at night
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something about what happened the day before, but the children who talk in their sleep.
When it happens to you for the first time, you'll be scared at best, but in reality, it doesn't matter.
This is a positive sleep disorder called sleep-talking.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, more than one of you has been told that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon may occur occasionally (once in a lifetime, for example, during a high fever), or regularly (every day, once a week, once a month), the next day the child cannot remember anything.
There's no single reason for this phenomenon.
Often, people look for connections to other phenomena in sleep, such as nightmares, panic attacks at night, bedwetting, sleep-talking, but there is no reason for this.
As we mentioned earlier, it can be a result of high fiber, stressful situations, or overwork.
Anyway, this is a little-researched phenomenon.
The frequency with which it occurs is highly variable.
It may be that you speak quietly in individual words, whisper, or it may be quite the opposite (crying, crying, long discussions).
In cases where the expression is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and consult a specialist to check whether there is a problem that causes anxiety and thus develops.
We said it's a positive disorder, so it's not treated unless it's associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, with sleep apnea or with stress).
What you can do is take a series of simple prevention measures:
Try not to excite the child before bedtime.
So, choosing quiet play for the child and avoiding stressful TV shows that are terrible and a little too wild.
For the nervous children who are recommended relaxation, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a measure of inner calm.
It helps the child sleep peacefully.
If talking in your sleep occurs once, try to keep calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child and the next day, he won't be able to remember anything that happened.
Useful Advice
Don't wake it up.
It's no use, because the child is unconscious, so you'll tear it out of its sleep.
Although the child is talking, it is sleeping, so it is resting.
Remember, if the child shows signs of being frightened after a few appearances, it is recommended that counseling be sought or that the reason for the child's fear be determined.
If they understand what it says (which is not so common), the child does not feel pressured to conduct an interrogation and get more information.
You won't be able to do anything with that because when the child is asleep, he's unconscious and can't think about it.
Also, you'll hear what it says, but you won't know what it's dreaming and why it's saying it, so be careful about interpreting the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
