Conversation - The Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice that Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public's trust, which had been severely shaken by the blood-tainted scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
It is well known that the national blood banks managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood service were contaminated with HIV and hepatitis C during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public discontent, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to develop guidelines to prevent a repeat of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to issue his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for managing blood banks in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to Gélineau and Krever's reports, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, only 38% of people had confidence in the blood-preservation system in Quebec, recalls Dr Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood supplies and through the work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public's trust,' she says, before proudly pointing out that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr Décary is aware that 'trust is extremely fragile'.
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has been acting on the precautionary principle.
At the time, we were seeing a number of cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
So we have referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that you use exclusion measures when you don't know it and when a disease is only slowly progressing, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is manifested by degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
So this incident showed us that the precautionary principle we applied makes perfect sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid test (NST), which allows the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, rather than the antibodies to the virus, as was the case with previous tests.
NSTs have made it possible to shorten the incubation period between the time a person is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, she explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
This significantly reduced the risk that certain donors could be infected without being aware of it and without being detected.
These improvements have made it possible to reduce the risk of AIDS transmission through blood transfusions to a considerable extent.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of HIV-infected blood.
` In other words, that means you would have to distribute 12 million cans of blood before someone would get HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmission to occur through a blood can.
I believe that nowadays, it is safe to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health,' says the head of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens might get into your system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through blood, appeared on Réunion Island.
We must keep a watchful eye,' Dr Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Québec must provide a safe supply and also an adequate supply.
` demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population is also affecting the blood donor network, which represents on average only 3% of Quebec's eligible blood donors. '
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of donors are rejected because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is common are barred from donating blood for a year.
` With this 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But you have to replace the members of this donor network when they get older and can't donate anymore.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is especially difficult to keep them and to get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely have time to spend an hour donating blood,' laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only preserved blood but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being placed in interim storage at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
In the umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
` A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
̋We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,' explains Dr Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood draw-down programme as very popular.
̋Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to this because Hema-Québec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly programme in all hospitals in Québec.
