Free Speech - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In its issue of 17 September, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, deputy director general of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
It confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company has filed a six million-dollar libel suit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they judge not by the truth, especially in cases of slander, but by the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to speak out against it.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defence and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal battles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also discourages anyone who dares to re-engage with the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of things to the public.
Contrary to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas and not by the use of batons.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had opened its books and files and opened up a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent fact-finding teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters in support of the writers of Noir Canada with a wave of the hand.
I would like to ask Mr Garver how he can simultaneously ask for a 'public' debate and ignore the opinions of this public?
It seems that in the vice president's world, that word only includes the lavishly paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the writers and editors of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gagging complaint (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just issued a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, asking them to stop using the term...).
Mr. Garver's surreal speech aside, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to research and discuss issues that don't appeal to the rich corporations of the world, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to curb this kind of unjustified lawsuits.
