What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On October 8, the trial of János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The accused are charged in particular with involvement in organised crime, gross negligence, damage and fraud, and other offences, including falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, the funds raised from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often supported by false invoices.
State funds and grants from the local authority - HUF 65 million in total - are said to have been partly transferred to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly to the coffers of private individuals.
The investigation authorities have stated that fictitious invoices were presented when the tendering fees were used and that the associations failed to fulfil their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were forged.
The invoice blocks were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, and the circular seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was taken on that round trip north of Lake Platte to which István Lados was sent by János Tzuslag.
During this "exploration tour", Lados was to locate guesthouses and restaurants.
He requested invoices for consumption in order to be able to issue invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour and the Municipality of Budapest based on these templates.
These bills are said to have been manipulated in the main by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, who we believe was responsible for drafting the reports.
One of the targets of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer hall.
As can be seen from two invoices issued by Zuzlag and Co in 2003, the catering establishment was said to have hosted the 90 members of Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now the manager says that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious errors of form and content.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at a time, is said to have accommodated 130 guests, according to the invoice.
The imagination of the counterfeiters was apparently no more limited than it was in the case of Pigal Kft., a catering company whose accounts, according to the prosecution, do not even contain the records of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
As the CEO Győző Farkas told hvg.hu, he immediately knew that these were fake documents when he was presented with documents by the prosecutor's office during an interview.
"Our company name and tax number were misplaced on the stamp".
Furthermore, apart from the formal errors, the fact that the establishment was supposed to have accommodated 100 people was also incorrect, when it has a total of 11 rooms which cannot possibly accommodate so many people.
The Commission also stated that the bill included a meal, but that the restaurant had not been in operation for some time.
The diligent counterfeiters also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offered trips abroad and so included Hungary trips on the cash bill, which also contradicted the company's accounting practices.
As it became clear during the investigation, they also included VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on a total of four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company charges only 15% VAT instead of 25%, and the employees issue only automatic invoices, but the forged documents were handwritten.
Another mistake made by the accountants was that in one case they had indicated 'transport of goods' as a service provided, although this is not offered by the investment advisory firm, the prosecutor's office said.
Further formal errors - incorrect invoice format, incorrect stamp - were responsible for exposing the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont as forgeries.
The same applies to Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose managers claimed that they had never issued the invoices.
Another 'mistake' was made by the counterfeiters at HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: this company was in the process of being dissolved at the time (2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was alleged to have dined there - the warehouse manager therefore stated that he had not issued the invoices himself.
Deliberately forged
The other group of accountants are people who were well aware that they would have to make fictitious invoices.
At the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation has issued invoices for the benefit of the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, amounting to about HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also currently in liquidation, is also alleged to have cooperated with Zuschlag and Co. In 2003, the company allegedly provided the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület associations with false invoices for a total value of HUF 5 million relating to services not provided.
However, there was also little transaction as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, which the parties concerned forgot to record in their documents.
The third group of accountants consists of persons who are directly connected with the accused.
One of them is Ivan Kubatov, the mailman for the Ukrainian CEO of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based but unavailable fuel and vehicle trading company.
This company is alleged to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components worth a total of about HUF 18 million between October and December 2005.
According to the investigating authority, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, acted as buyer of these invoices.
The company's managing director was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be served by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, during the investigation Kubatov admitted to having issued invoices in the name of the company to the associations Atlasz and Hoppá, and to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and to having collected the equivalent of these invoices himself.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were allegedly founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Iván Kubatov.
In fact, however, none of these companies were active, which the defendant claimed was due to a lack of orders.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was in charge of preparing the company's constitution documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations associated with the contract, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is alleged to have issued 15 invoices to the organisations for a total value of HUF 14.2 million on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecution believes Kubatov may have collected 10% of the invoice amount and the VAT each.
Kubatov is alleged to have even abused the company Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices - in this case the invoices were attached to Biztos Pont's applications.
The company Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied to the non-profit organisation of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ('TMA') in January 2006.
Both received 500,000 forints each, but misused the funds.
In order to cover this up, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices of Works Team Kft.
These bills were, by the way, found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
The trial is now expected to include a confession by some of the accused about the practice of counterfeiting invoices, as they have already been submitted to the prosecution.
It could be a sensation if the main defendant, János Zuzsa, decides to make a full confession.
His previous statements were less detailed, and although he had promised several times to report everything in detail, his confession is still pending.
The question therefore remains whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have concluded a pact with him to make good most of the damage of HUF 50 million and whether Zuschlag is prepared to assume responsibility in return.
It is quite possible, however, that Zuschlag is now playing the "offended" after his requests for relief of his detention and house arrest were ignored.
While other criminals who have caused far greater damage by economic crimes and have not compensated for it are at large, or at least under house arrest, Zuschlag is denied this possibility.
The Psychology of Over-Bidding - or Why We Are Willing to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bargain.
Neuroscientists and economists at New York University have now succeeded in uncovering the neuroeconomic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people are willing to pay even higher prices in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, because they do not want to lose.
Researchers have tried to explore the neurological pattern of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was asked to play the lottery while the other participated in a playful activity - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
Both games offered participants the chance to win money, but the participants' striatum, a complex beneath the cerebral cortex, was shown to be more active in auction losers, where outbiding the opponent plays a major role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the nervous system's "self-reward".
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by the avoidance of overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group also conducted research on the traceability of money.
In this case, three groups would have to bid against one partner on different terms.
The control group was told the true value of the product, and then they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a reward of $15 if they emerged victorious.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a losing game.
The only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on winning for one group and losing for the other.
But as evidence of the hypothesis put forward by neurologists, the members of the "losing" group were willing to bet more than those in the control or "winning" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
The reason for the behaviour observed in auctions so far has been the joy of winning or the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved by imaging neuroscience, so that we now have a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at 100,000 in this country, but only 7,000 are being treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water); in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as semen, faeces or saliva).
Vaccination against the A and B viruses is recommended for travellers, but there is no vaccine for the C virus.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Then the yellowing of the skin and eyes occurs, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery may take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-related, far more serious diseases, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that only one in ten people with the disease is estimated to be on medication.
Hepatitis C can also be serious, leading to cirrhosis and liver cancer if left untreated.
Most people infected with the disease are unaware of their illness because the pathogen is insidiously destroying liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of people with chronic hepatitis C worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, it is advisable to consult your doctor at the first sign of an unknown origin.
If detected early, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, and the risk of infection and cancer is prevented.
World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on 30 September and was first organized by patient organisations worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic viral hepatitis, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research shows that religious faith is like a "painkiller" that has already eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to investigate the extent to which belief in God affects a person's sense of pain, reported the British newspaper The Telegraph.
In the course of the rather bizarre study, 12 devotees and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
In fact, brain-scan technology has shown that Catholics can activate the part of their brain that regulates pain.
The study was the first in a research project involving philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
The experiment involved attaching a sparkling device to the left hand of the subject, which gave the electroshock.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: one, a 17th-century painting of the Mother of God by Sassoferrato, and the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermes".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would cause a religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other paintings and was found to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages, while they were asked to look at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God they felt "safe", as if "concerned", and they felt "calm and peaceful".
While looking at the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, another participant in the experiment, said that similar effects could be produced with other powerful images, even in atheists, if only one found the appropriate photograph.
"We would have to find an image that evokes very positive feelings, like a mother or a father", says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases it does", says Wright.
After these excellent results, the only question remains what effect a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another similar painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would a high-quality Virgin Mary produce even better results?
You are what you say you are
On its tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that it is in people's pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the executives at Google.
To skeptics who are plagued by Orwellian horror visions, he says, they would be missing the essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, thus moving closer to the company's original goal of "ordering all the information in the world".
Schmidt explained that after ten years of changing the world, Google is still in the early stages of information gathering.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google could answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job is really right for me?" but that software programs are not yet able to do so because they do not know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that their Internet searches record the search terms, the IP addresses from which the search was made and the pages visited.
For example, the Personalized Search introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save and access their own search history so that the results can be generated much more accurately later, and the same logic is used for the so-called "recommendations" that the system uses to recommend tailored products and services based on past preferences.
But users are wondering what happens if data is misused - "If you look at what I do" - and some are worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is the fear-inducing factor, rather than guilt or fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or rebellion against power, that is the reason for many Internet users' rejection.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored but also passed on to third parties where appropriate, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent anti-pedophilia operation in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called Orkut, which also allowed the pedophiles to be identified.
However, users concerned about their privacy were able to take a break in May when Google and the civil rights organization EFF successfully sued the FBI, according to which Google can no longer be forced by any provision of the Constitution to give information to the FBI on secret request.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the release of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms in reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but it has been withheld the list of individual users, or their web and search term lists, for two months retroactively.)
Google's image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to give out their personal data because they fear losing their privacy and privacy by using Google services are lashing out at the company with the indignation that befits self-described conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google does not require its users to provide identification codes, unlike Microsoft, and provides its services free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems much more attractive, youthful and cooler than the software giant's official practices.
On the other hand, geeks are keenly aware of the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has been brought into focus, especially in recent years, by the term "Web 2.0".
The Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, meaning that users deliberately leave their mark and use the available channels of communication, and even if the extent varies from person to person, the main thing remains the same, namely to be seen publicly.
The average teenager can manage their profile on multiple community portals at once - from Facebook to Xanga, they can connect them through other services like Twitter, or music services like last.fm, and they can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm.
And as a series of other examples prove: looking at the party photos from the previous night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee is fired for being too honest in his blog about his anger at the management of the company - one thing is certain: The concept of "privacy" has been completely reinterpreted.
The online life is what you give away - a way of saying the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And if you're trying to keep something secret, or even to get around Google's monopoly, you can do that - like with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine but deliberately leaves no trace.
Many people deliberately avoid registering on community sites to avoid being found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphics tools and RSS feeds, can also be handled with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile of the user.
Meanwhile, public opinion is waiting in vain for Google to show its true face.
With a current value of $156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), the advertising space of AdWords/AdSense threatens the revenues of advertising agencies, and the increasingly rapidly introduced services are causing headaches not only for Microsoft but also for other software developers.
Critics, however, find the opposite to worrying: for example, the company management completely rejected a protest by employees after the fees of the company's own kindergarten were doubled, and the management thought that the multiple meals of the employees were too expensive.
The company's internal policy is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available.However, events in the coming months and years could turn things around: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project is now assuming proportions that the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are more concerned about the "Health" system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database already provides the stuff for the next generation of science fiction writers -- like "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow that describes in the best Orwellian way a future where humans become terrifyingly accessible thanks to data that Google collects.
