Intelligent car mimics the flight of bumblebees
What better way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents than to mimic the obstacle sensors of nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees to create new accident-prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car with bee characteristics, which is controlled by a car robot, with the aim of helping develop a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", much like our own "shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The bee's complex eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays a vital role.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, researchers have taken up the idea of a laser-controlled rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a 180-degree field of view of 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is detected in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it were not, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, because this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield, a layer within which accidents are currently still considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a split second.
However, unlike bees, the deflection cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the tire's rotation.
While bees have endless opportunities to avoid other bees, the researchers in the car robot have been able to use only rotation, or acceleration and deceleration.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries which are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it was about the instinctive, intelligent response, less about the processing of the data, and even less about the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few inputs per second.
It doesn't have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a handful of KB of memory at a time.
It doesn't need gigabytes and megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the instantaneous collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next ten years.
Another application of the technology could be in GPS satellite navigation, whereby the driver is deliberately guided around obstacles and thus to the destination.
