Industrial prices continued to rise
As the Central Statistical Office pointed out, domestic sales prices in August 2008 increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007.
Export prices were up by 1.1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9% compared to the previous year.
Due to domestic and export price changes, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices increased only slightly, by 0.1%, compared with the previous month.
Manufacturing sales prices also rose only slightly - 0.1 per cent - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was in leather goods (2.8 percent), primarily bags and belts, which rose 4.6 percent, and shoes, which rose 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials led to a substantial increase in prices for chemicals and manufacturing (1.6%).
The price decreases were recorded in crude oil processing (1.4%), electrical and technical equipment (0.9%) and slightly in wood processing (0.1%).
Prices in the papermaking industry, as well as in publishing and printing, remained unchanged.
In other branches of manufacturing, price increases ranged from 0.2 to 0.9%.
In the main domestic markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supply, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly as a result of the increase in gas prices introduced on 1 July.
Looking at the domestic markets of manufacturing industry year on year, crude oil processing prices rose the most (32.4 per cent).
The metalworking sector saw a 13.2 percent increase, while the increase in the manufacture of food, beverages, and tobacco was 11 percent.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5%) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3%).
The rate of inflation in the other manufacturing industries ranged from 0.6 to 9.1%.
Overall, manufacturing prices climbed 10.2 percent last year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent compared to the previous year.
The highest price increase (0.7%) was recorded in August in the domestic market for fixed assets.
In the manufacturing sectors for consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3%, while in the energy and processing sectors they remained stable compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 compared to the same period in 2007 was observed in the energy and reuse sector (16.8%).
The consumer goods sector recorded a 6.8% increase in prices and the capital goods sector a 1.4% decrease.
Industry's export prices, measured in forints, rose by 1.1% in August compared with the previous month, but declined by 3.9% year on year.
The domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, and compared with the August 2007 exchange rate, it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and by 15.9 percent against the dollar.
