'The scientific evidence shows that the EU is facing a clear risk that requires rapid action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In the light of these scientific findings, we must review the control systems already in place to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology".
The independent scientific committee was commissioned by Brussels in view of the widespread use of portable musical instruments among young people.
'The scientists confirm that their concerns are justified and that the European Commission will now work with other Member States and the parties concerned to examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise emitted by portable musical and similar devices.'
The Commission has already adopted a European standard limiting the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB.
This damage can be greatly reduced by using solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of exposure.
In its report, the European Union's Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to music at a loud level (above 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, they have already exceeded the legal limits for maximum noise levels in the workplace.
Those who exceed this limit are at risk of complete hearing loss within five years.
This is 5-10% of the users of such devices, which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
