The financial collapse is also affecting journalists, as you can already feel the cuts in the newspapers, and many blame the Internet, the "killer" of the printed press.
Five hundred American journalists were interviewed by the PEW Research Center about their situation and their mental control regarding the future.
Today, almost all journalists are pessimistic about their future.
However, they did not express any real concern about the general credibility of the information concerning the competent authorities.
You don't feel as alone as you used to.
The problem for American journalists is money.
The 2008 crisis is for these journalists a crisis of an economic model that has been destroyed.
Added to the problems are the cuts to the newsroom, the room where the editors work to put together the paper.
This is a problem that must be solved  according to the journalists interviewed  if traditional journalism, as understood by the general public, is not to be allowed to shrink significantly.
A clear but complicated pessimism is what fills the American journalist today.
Six out of ten journalists and senior executives in the print media think that journalism at the national level is on the wrong track.
In the local sector, it is even 65% for executives.
Printed versus broadcast.
It's not hard for journalists to imagine where the web is going.
The major publishing groups are making their way to the Internet, which many consider the "killer" of the printed press.
The "economic pressure" felt by journalists has increased by up to 79%.
The 500 journalists interviewed admitted to wanting to join the new technology, hoping "it will bring something good to journalism".
The biggest rift in American journalism today is between the editors of the newsroom and the reporters who work for them.
56% of editors at national level are confident that their reporters share their values with them, compared with only 23% at local level.
Some people think it has to do with "workplace safety".
The proportion of managers who are afraid of losing their jobs within three years is 47% at national level.
For journalists, it is 30%.
The issue of "safe working" in the team (our "editors") is always a hot topic in the USA.
Only 13% of journalists work under contract.
In a huge nation like the United States, with 300 million people and thousands of newspapers, magazines, radio and TV stations and Internet operators, employers offer as they please and so it becomes a take it or leave it question.
The editors-in-chief are often paid very high salaries, while the editor can sometimes earn only 10,000 euros a month, plus pensions and insurance benefits.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, but I am not sure that we can accept them.
But American journalists, as they themselves admit, often get "sick" during the year.
It's a matter of climate.
