The elite is in danger
The phenomenon was already apparent a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the White House's $700 billion austerity package: a large part of the American people were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times report on how the ongoing crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favoured government institutions and the business community, and the neoconservatives who are hostile to those in Washington and the financial world, and are winning voters, especially in the South and the center of the States.
This part of the party owes its rise mainly to the voice of the man I mentioned above.
The example just given is only a small part of the great changes that the current economic earthquake is heralding or even already representing: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond.
The crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events which are finally taking shape and coming to light in these new conditions, both in the States and in Europe.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state, combined with a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is in fact a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with the outside world and at the same time manage a huge amount of the assets of households living in a single country.
This poses a direct political problem for governments: how to deal with the families involved, who are also a huge mass of voters.
The crisis is thus economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined and lost its right to speak: the EU, which is divided into various national and international conflicts and cannot find a common path, has provided a clear example of this.
The European Union is now facing a crisis in which the United States is the only country in the world that can survive without foreign aid.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, but I am not sure that we can accept them.
The new emphasis on the national element is also in perfect harmony with the increasing importance recently attached in the economy to a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long ago entered a world of interconnectedness, a world of ever more differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we suddenly have to realize how our future will depend more and more on the essentials of the material: water, crops and oil.
While all of these can be transported from one place to another, they are still at most bound to a narrowly defined piece of land  a territory.
Thus, one who has such a territory has an advantage over another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I shall now turn to the second new feature, which, however, requires a short delay.
When you say territory, when you say government, when you say politics, you mean leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there's the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, the need for someone who knows how to run things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation at the existing leadership, especially the economic leadership, which has proved inadequate and full of shadow zones.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, and I am sure that the Commission will be able to do so in the near future.
It seems that the conviction is being formed among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but also their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is increasingly alien and superstitious to the majority.
The demand for leadership is thus fuelling underground a branching but powerful movement to disempower the ruling class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in unforeseen "riots" by voters and the sudden shift in collective mood of recent times, starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, and the rebellion of American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role).
It seems as if the old elite, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their magazines, their intellectual believers, some would say their format, have more and more problems understanding and therefore less representative value in relation to what is happening in the lower social strata of the West today, and this is being exacerbated by the financial crisis and driven to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply an exaggeration to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes peeled is not.
The Super Glue That Blows Up Walls
Defeat the forces of gravity with a glue and climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now seems to be close to its goal.
Using a piece of glue applied to a surface of just one square inch, researchers have been able to fix a 100-pound body to a vertical wall.
The study, published in the journal STUDIO, published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is an evolution of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of the glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged in a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the gecko's feet, which are covered with microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect grip.
Tests with materials such as Teflon glass and sandpaper have shown that the new glue is ten times stronger than the grip of the reptile's feet and "easily removes it from the wall", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a transient adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe, but researchers are thinking about a less fascinating use, like connecting electrical devices, because nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in the field of space.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH  Also at the University of California, Berkeley, a new type of glue is being studied.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, scientists in California present a glue made of microfibers that, like hair, cleans itself of dust by moving on a surface, thus maintaining a perfect bond.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time as certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on their absorption by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly warned of the risks of packaged and fresh fruit juices when they are used in connection with medication, and at the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia he warned that one glass of apple, orange, or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital medications to the point of virtually eliminating them, putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medications, including antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytics and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
DANGERED MEDICINES  In a report two years ago, the same agency warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture and urged them to be careful about what they drink in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or methadone.
It's not just grapefruit. Experts say that orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit medications.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately communicated to the various international manufacturers, who are free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package insert and, if there is still confusion, do not be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor", stresses the expert from the ANSA agency.
