According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value", but also a banalist with a "very aggressive style, particularly against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration".
Open Office, the third version of the anti-Microsoft package is released.
The day has come for the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source software that is gaining a growing number of users as a free replacement for Microsoft Office, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, overseen by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now being presented with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more spartanly designed start menu, it is now finally fully compatible with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest standard ISO version.
The Commission also noted the compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
There are also some new features, such as the ability to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send them via email, and the ability to import PDF files into graphics modules while maintaining the original look and feel of the page.
This is how "hybrid" PDFs can now be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format to include the elements of a spreadsheet and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple users, avoiding conflicts of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question to guarantee a better proofreading process.
Some companies are in the process of releasing various OpenOffice features on the cloud, while the final result is expected to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html.
The program is available for Windows and Mac OS, as well as the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or office.
While the free of charge feature may be an incentive for the spread of the software in private households, it is also in the business sector where OpenOffice could make a big leap: after all, several public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, it is not even lacking in training, which is an optimal aid for small and medium-sized enterprises and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-compatible text editor; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations like with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases instead of the more popular Access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The target for 2008 is 5 million downloads, a target that can be easily exceeded with 3.6 million already achieved.
