The New York Times asks: "Is Italy racist?"
Italy, "the former country of emigrants, has recently become one of the countries of choice for immigrants", who are only reluctantly accepted.
Does this make the Belpaese a nation of racists? asks the New York Times in a long article devoted entirely to the issue of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young man of Burkina Faso origin, Abdul William Guibre, who was murdered in Milan a month ago after stealing a packet of biscuits.
The case illustrates what the Times calls the "paradox of the North": the northern regions are where "the most integration and job opportunities exist", yet "the highest levels of anti-immigration sentiment and the greatest support for the Northern League".
Confirming the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the Times cites further episodes of intolerance from Milan, Rome, Parma, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
