Students are victims of high room rents of up to 900 euros
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious forms: whole groups of students are effectively losing their right to study because their families are not able to support them at this level", says Laura Mariani, head of Sunia.
In addition, most rental offers contain a number of violations: free contracts, no registration, no rent limit, unauthorised subletting.
Sunia believes that exceptional measures are needed to reduce rents by revising the tax system.
A closer look at the study shows that in Milan, a place to sleep in the Brianza district costs about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350-400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the university districts, a bed costs 250/280 euros, a single room 370-500 euros.
In Rome, prices in the university districts are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a double room.
The rent is only slightly lower in the neighbourhoods around the other universities in Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who avoid the suburbs can save money: 300 euros for a place to sleep and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples, you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a bed costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest towns, prices are lower, but they have a greater impact on the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25-30% above average are demanded by foreign students.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso  the cities are closing their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas are closing due to the multiplex cinema concessions.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
This image by director Giuseppe Tornatore is a powerful description of what is happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-screen complexes in the periphery, means the death in the long run of the single-screen cinema in the centre.
The film, which won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix at Cannes 20 years ago, tells the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia for a world that has been lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, the huge number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close, largely due to the closure of cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions that have registered the largest number of these modern cinemas: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy tops the list, 81 being in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "While it is useful that new structures are also being built, the priority is to preserve the existing one, because when a cinema in the city closes, not all its regular customers are ready to go to a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
It is a shame from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
The sector would need between EUR 16 and 18 million a year to survive.'
The first Italian city to decide to protect its old cinemas through an agreement between the municipality and Anec, the first such agreement in Italy, is Bologna, which is the first Italian city to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historic centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for cinema operators and local public transport benefits: access to restricted areas of the centre and parking at lower rates.
'It is a welcome initiative,' says Giuseppe Tornatore, 'and I hope that other cities will follow our example and come up with new concepts.
But we certainly need better audio and video equipment to counter the superpower of multiplex theatres, because today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been toying with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
Links between politics and the 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
