When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly come running.
It's an unquenchable source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is looking at, and also trying to occupy, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years, and it is no accident that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
The idea of marine energy was abandoned when the price of oil plummeted around 1980, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energy produced by ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy produced by nuclear power plants today.
And then there are the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to switch to offshore energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies in the traditional energy sector are now turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies", says a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering working with us".
It is about getting the approval from the U.S. Energy Commission to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially when one considers that Alaska is the one where oil is still extracted by the United States and President Bush only recently started the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also investing in the new industry, although the details are not known, but observers say there is growing interest.
There are still technologies to improve.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts of environmentalists have not yet been cleared.
So far, projects such as the one in Portugal and also in Scotland have been rather small in scale and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies with a much greater environmental impact.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure inside the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
The Commission has already proposed four such plants, which are still awaiting government approval, and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, is already generating power for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The water moves during the tides to power the turbines, which, through the resulting rotation, feed the generator.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
The Institute for Electricity Research says that the potential of tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although irregular, tides are better predictable than wind currents, sunlight, and waves, and thus a more reliable source of power.
It is tidal energy that has led states like New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 -- up to $35 million is planned for 2009.
